@using System;
@using Sandbox;
@using Sandbox.UI;
@namespace Gambit.UI
@inherits PanelComponent

@*
	ONE STRING ON ONE PLATE. That is the entire contract, and it is not modesty — it is the
	only WorldPanel shape this repo has ever got to render.

	Five rounds of bugs on the clock were ALL layout, and none were data: the world scale,
	the `root` rule, nowrap/flex-shrink, plate-vs-text centring, and the absolute-positioning
	ancestor. The seam was correct throughout — gambit_clock printed the right seconds while
	the face showed a dot. The common cause: the working shape (MarqueeNumberPanel, the table
	plaque) is `root` at 100% plus ONE absolutely-positioned 100% child, and it CANNOT BE
	COMPOSED. Put a box between root and the text div and `position: absolute` retargets to
	it, so every centring rule silently means something else.

	So the clock composes in 3D instead: two of these on two mesh plates, with a mesh bar
	between them (ChessRing.BuildStationClock, driven by World/TableClock.cs). Each panel
	here has one text div and no siblings, so there is nothing left to compose wrongly.

	This is byte-for-byte MarqueeNumberPanel's structure. The ONLY additions are Text (vs a
	fixed Number) and the State class, and State only ever sets `color` — it adds no box, no
	sibling, and no layout. Keep it that way: the moment a second element lands in here, this
	is TableClockPanel again and the five rounds start over. A second string is a second
	plate.
*@

<root>
	<div class="t @State">@Text</div>
</root>

<style>
	@@import "WallTheme.scss";

	root {
		width: 100%;
		height: 100%;
		pointer-events: none;
	}

	/*
		nowrap AND flex-shrink: 0 — one rule, two halves, and the most expensive line in
		CLAUDE.md. A flex item's default is to shrink; a shrunk text div does not
		ellipsize, it WRAPS; and a div's auto height does not grow for wrapped text, so
		the text is clipped to a sliver of its first line. That is how "2:48" rendered as
		a single dot while "W" (one char, cannot wrap) rendered fine beside it.

		They are belt-and-braces here — this div has no siblings to be squeezed by — and
		they stay anyway. They cost nothing and they are exactly what was missing.
	*/
	.t {
		position: absolute;
		left: 0;
		top: 0;
		width: 100%;
		height: 100%;
		display: flex;
		align-items: center;
		justify-content: center;
		text-align: center;
		white-space: nowrap;
		flex-shrink: 0;
		font-family: $wall-font;
		font-size: 130px;
		font-weight: bold;
		color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.45);
	}

	/* The running side is the only one worth looking at. Its PLATE also lightens (a mesh
	   tint, set by TableClock) — this is the text half of that pair. */
	.t.on { color: #e8e6df; }

	/* Under TimeControl.PanicSeconds — the same threshold the panic beep starts at, which
	   is why it is a shared constant and not a 10f typed in two files. */
	.t.panic { color: #ff5f5f; }
</style>

@code {
	/// <summary>The one string. Set per-frame by <see cref="Gambit.World.TableClock"/>;
	/// the hash below means "per-frame" costs a repaint only when a digit changes.</summary>
	[Property] public string Text { get; set; } = "";

	/// <summary>A DISPLAY state, not a game state: "" (dim), "on" (bright) or "panic" (red).
	/// Colour only — see the note above about what may not go in here.
	///
	/// <para>Named for what it looks like rather than what it means, because two different
	/// callers mean different things by it: a clock plate is "on" when that seat's clock is
	/// running, and the lead badge is "on" always, being a readout rather than an idle face.
	/// A state called <c>ticking</c> would have been a lie on the badge.</para></summary>
	[Property] public string State { get; set; } = "";

	/// <summary>Hashed as the RENDERED STRING, never the raw float behind it. Hashing
	/// seconds would repaint every face of every live table in the ring every frame;
	/// hashing the text repaints exactly when a digit changes.</summary>
	protected override int BuildHash() => System.HashCode.Combine( Text, State );
}
